pharmacokinetics of ampicillin during P_G agneta philipson from the departments of infectious diseases and of obstetrics and gynecology, danderyd hospital, danderyd; and the department of clinical pharmacology, karolinska hospital, stockholm, sweden levels of ampicillin in plasma and urine were studied in 26 P_G women during the 8 hr following an oral as well as an intravenous dose.
identical doses were given to the same women after P_G, and the resulting plasma and urine levels were compared.
plasma levels were significantly V_E_R_B during P_G than after.
the difference was unrelated to body weight and length of P_G but was associated with a significant V_E_R_B in P_K and renal P_K in P_G women.
recovery of ampicillin in urine during 8 hr was identical during P_G and after.
it is suggested that P_G women require V_E_R_B doses of ampicillin per kg of body weight than nonP_G women in order to achieve similar P_K in plasma.
the level of ampicillin in serum was measured 2 hr after the administration of a dose and was found to be below the lowest measurable level.

for investigation of whether the unexpectedly V_E_R_B level folV_E_R_Bing oral administration was due to P_G, the same woman was given a single oral test dose of 0.5 g of ampicillin a few months after delivery.
the serum level was measured after 2 hr and was found to be adequate.
the aim of the present study was to investigate whether a difference in plasma levels of ampicillin between P_G and nonP_G is a general phenomenon.

the present cross-over study clearly showed that the same amount of ampicillin, whether S_T_U_D_Y iv or orally, resulted in plasma levels that were significantly V_E_R_B in P_G than in nonP_G women.
the plasma levels during P_G were V_E_R_B than could be expected merely because of the V_E_R_B in mean body weight, which amounted to <5.9%.
the value for P_K of ampicillin was V_E_R_B during P_G than after, and the difference remained when the dose was calculated per kg of body weight.

that the V_E_R_B in plasma levels was not a simple parallel to the V_E_R_B in body weight during P_G was further suggested by the finding that there was no S_T_U_D_Y between the difference in P_K and the difference in weight for each individual during and after P_G.
there was also no S_T_U_D_Y between the length of P_G (nine to 36 weeks) and the V_E_R_B in peak levels in plasma, or P_K.
the difference in plasma levels was most likely due to V_E_R_B volumes of plasma and body water during P_G [3].
V_E_R_B volumes of plasma and total body water will be reflected in a V_E_R_B P_K for ampicillin in P_G women as compared with that in nonP_G women.
the difference in P_K may also reflect cha during P_G in the S_T_U_D_Y of ampici to plasma proteins and peripheral tissues.

the amounts of ampicillin recovered in urine were similar during and after P_G, but the plasma levels during P_G were lower; therefore the c1, value in P_G became V_E_R_B.
since c1, varies indirectly with tl/2, the value for c1p will V_E_R_B as the value for t/2 decreases.

the lack of a significant difference in P_K of the oral dose during and after P_G agrees well with the similar amounts of ampicillin recovered in urine and makes it unlikely that the P_K of orally S_T_U_D_Y ampicillin is V_E_R_B during P_G.

these results suggest that no V_E_R_B in the dosage of mecillinam/pivmecillinam is necessary during P_G in spite of some V_E_R_B in pharmacokinetics.

hobbins, m.d.* abstract the pharmacokinetics of theophylline was determined in six P_G, nonsmoking women in P_G at term following a single bolus infusion of 5.6 mg/kg of aminophylline over 20 minutes.

compared to values reported in the literature for nonpregnant adult nonsmokers, the volume distribution (mean 573 Ã”Ã¸Î© 53 ml/kg) and P_K rate (mean .88 Ã”Ã¸Î© .24 ml/kg/min) of theophylline is V_E_R_B in P_G, but the P_K (mean 7.95 Ã”Ã¸Î© 2 hrs) remains unaltered.

similar doses of aminophylline can therefore be used in P_G and nonP_G adults who do not smoke cigarettes, but the infusion rate required to maintain a mean serum concentration of 10jug/ml (0.5 mg/kg/hr) is almost half that initially reported in the literature.

the serum theophylline P_K in P_G venous and mixed P_G at delivery were almost identical, which implies that theophylline V_E_R_B the placenta rapidly and that the fetus represents a "shallow" drug compartment.

the same dose regimen for intravenous aminophylline has been advocated for P_G patients,1 although the pharmacokinetics of aminophylline following intravenous bolus infusion has not been determined in P_G women.

to our knowledge, the pharmacokinetics of aminophylline has only been addressed by a single study10 which reported the P_K rate, volume of distribution, and P_K of aminophylline in three asthmatic P_G women following oral administration, but failed to report the smoking status of the patients.
the purpose of this paper is to report on the pharmacokinetics of aminophylline in P_G women in P_G at term, who do not smoke cigarettes, and on the P_G of the drug.
patients were given a single intravenous dose of 5.6 mg/kg of aminophylline over a 20-minute period.

the magnitude of this effect is such that quantitatively significant changes in the pharmacokinetic and pharmacodynamic characteristics of certain drugs may be expected to occur during P_G (in addition to possible changes caused by other P_G-related effects such as V_E_R_B activity of drug-metabolizing enzyme systems).

attempts to determine the effect ofpregnancy on in vivo pharmacokinetics must take into consideration the possibility of concurrent changes in the activity of drug-metabolizing enzyme systems and in the serum S_T_U_D_Y of drugs.
reduction of both enzyme activity and S_T_U_D_Y may result in little or no net V_E_R_B of total drug P_K and therefore of steadystate total drug serum concentration produced by a dosage regimen.

this is so because V_E_R_B enzyme activity will V_E_R_B the intrinsic P_K and because the total P_K of many drugs is the product of intrinsic P_K and serum free fraction (which is V_E_R_B when S_T_U_D_Y is V_E_R_B)." the distribution of drugs between mother and fetus, and therefore the plasma concentration of total drug in newborn infants of mothers who took these drugs during P_G, is affected by S_T_U_D_Y in P_G and fetal plasma.

the free P_K of phenytoin in P_G and fetal plasma of goats, and of salicylic acid in P_G and newborn serum of humans are equal under postdistribution conditions."' 21 since the serum S_T_U_D_Y of salicylic acid and certain (but not all) other drugs is more extensive in the serum of newborn infants than in the serum of their mothers, the total serum concentration of these drugs is V_E_R_B in infants than in their mothers under postdistribution conditions. 6' 7 in view of the important clinical implications of V_E_R_B S_T_U_D_Y of drugs during P_G, we determined the serum S_T_U_D_Y of several drugs in P_G women as a function of P_G time and also at various P_G intervals.

by 72 h the blood level was below 5 ng. ml- 1. 482 discussion betaxolol is a selective [3-adrenoceptor blocking agent with V_E_R_B bioavailibility ( -~80% ), limited plasma S_T_U_D_Y ( ~ 50%) and elevated liposolubility (morselli et al., 1983; beresford and heel, 1986).
the blood P_K P_K in adult hypertensive patients ranges from 16 to 20 h (bianchetti et al. 1986).
the results now obtained in P_G women and newborns are consistent with its physicochemical properties and its pharmacokinetic profile in hypertensive S_T_U_D_Y.
the apparent blood P_K halflife (15-22 h) was also within the range observed in adult patients undergoing chronic treatment with the drug.
on this basis it appears that the pharmacokinetic profile of betaxolol is not modified in P_G women in the P_G.
betaxolol P_K in P_G P_G were 2-3 fold V_E_R_B than those in blood up to 24-48 h after dosing.

comparison with data for other [3-blockers indicates a V_E_R_B P_G/blood ratios (2.5-10) for acebutolol and a similar value (1.6-4.5) for atenolol, metoprolol, oxprenoloi and propranolol (boutroy et al. 1986; kulas et al. 1984; liedholm et al. 1981; lundborg et al. 1981; sandstrom and regardh 1980; sioufi et al. 1984; thorley et al. 1983; white et al. 1984).
considering the drug P_K in the neonates, the apparent blood P_K ranged from 14.9 to 38.5 h, with an trend towards a negative S_T_U_D_Y with the P_G S_T_U_D_Y.
it is interesting that in newborns of less than 36 weeks, the apparent P_K was about 32% V_E_R_B (p < 0.01) than in the full-term neonates.
a similar, V_E_R_B blood P_K in newborns has been described for other [3-blockers (bianchetti et al. 1981; boutroy et al. 1982; rnbin et al. 1983; lindeberg et al. 1987).

a negative S_T_U_D_Y between plasma or blood P_K and P_G S_T_U_D_Y has been described for many other drugs which depend for their P_K on metabolic degradation or renal excretion (morselli et al. 1980).
the renal P_K of betaxolol in the neonate during thr first 72h of life was very V_E_R_B indeed (0.95- 3.53ml.min-1).
V_E_R_B renal P_K has only a very limited impact on the total P_K of the compound, since betaxolol is mostly cleared by metabolic degradation.
in a certain number of cases an V_E_R_B in the blood P_K was observed after 48-60 h of life.

such a phenomenon could be due to maturation of the physiological mechanisms important in drug excretion or to a V_E_R_B or disappearance of the possible pharmacodynamic effects of the drug on the heart, liver and kidney.
in conclusion, data on the pharmacokinetics of betaxolol in the P_G indicate that in the mothers the pharmacokinetic profile is similar to that observed in non P_G adult hypertensive patients.
the P_K in the neonate is moderately prolonged and there is a certain negative S_T_U_D_Y with the P_G S_T_U_D_Y.

analgesic drugs in P_G and plasma* the disposition ofsalicylic acid, phenacetin, caffeine, and codeine, and two metabolites, acetaminophen and morphine, was studied in P_G and plasma of two lactating mothers after single oral doses of a compound analgesic.
salicylic acid penetrated poorly into P_G, with peak levels of only 1.12 to 1.69 auglml, whereas peak plasma levels were 33 to 43.4 pglml.
the drug was also eliminated more slowly from P_G than plasma.
in contrast, caffeine and phenacetin P_K in P_G and plasma were similar, but P_G levels were somewhat V_E_R_B than plasma levels in both S_T_U_D_Y.
P_K of the metabolite, acetaminophen, from P_G was slower than from plasma (S_T_U_D_Y 1, half-hfe (P_K) of drug in P_G, 4.7 hr; P_K in plasma, 2.9 hr).
in both S_T_U_D_Y codeine P_K in P_G were 1.5 to 2.4 times as V_E_R_B as in plasma at the same times after drug.
metabolically produced morphine levels in P_G from both mothers were V_E_R_B but exceeded those in plasma after 1 hr.
similar calculations based on predicted steady-state P_G drug P_K in S_T_U_D_Y 2 indicated maximum P_G excretion of2.7% of the dose.
in each case caffeine was V_E_R_B in the P_G in the greatest amount.

although 5000 u of unfractionated heparin every 12 hours is usually effective prophylaxis for highrisk surgical patients, changes in the pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of unfractionated heparin during P_G make this regimen inadequate.1, 2 during the P_G of P_G, brancazio et al2 found both a V_E_R_B time to peak heparin effect and a V_E_R_B peak effect after subcutaneous administration of unfractionated heparin in P_G women compared with nonP_G women.
barbour et al1 demonstrated that heparin levels were below the therapeutic range for prophylaxis in 14 (100%) of 14 women receiving 5000 u of unfractionated heparin every 12 hours in the P_G.

even when the dose was V_E_R_B to 7500 u every 12 hours in the P_G and 10,000 u every 12 hours in the P_G, heparin levels were subtherapeutic in 5 (56%) of 9 patients in the P_G and 6 (47%) of 13 patients in the P_G.

the observed changes in the pharmacokinetics of unfractionated heparin are likely caused by physiologic alterations, such as V_E_R_B plasma volume, V_E_R_B glomerular filtration rate, and production of placental heparinase.

the maximum concentration of enoxaparin and the time to reach the maximum concentration that were observed in our study S_T_U_D_Y in the P_G period were similar to measurements observed in other studies.5, 11 enoxaparin appears to be completely bioavailable after subcutaneous injection.11 therefore the apparent P_K and the P_K calculated after subcutaneous injection will correspond to the actual systemic P_K and volume of distribution of enoxaparin.
the systemic P_K of enoxaparin has been reported to be 0.83 to 1.86 l/h11 and 0.83 Ã”Ã¸Î© 0.19 l/h.12 the apparent P_K observed in our study group ranged from 0.6 to 0.8 l/h.

the P_G of enoxaparin is reported to be 5.2 to 6.4 hours and is consistent with our findings.

because P_G, which is a measure of the average time a drug resides in the body, is determined both by P_K and volume of distribution and because both P_K and volume of distribution changed in our study patients, we observed essentially no change in P_G.

we have shown that the pharmacokinetics of the lowmolecular-weight heparin enoxaparin sodium, like unfractionated heparin, V_E_R_B in P_G.

because of normal physiologic changes in P_G, such as V_E_R_B plasma volume, V_E_R_B glomerular filtration rate, and production of placental heparinase, enoxaparin sodium appears to have a V_E_R_B P_K and V_E_R_B volume of distribution during early P_G compared with the P_G period in the same women.

despite the current and potential applications of artemisinin derivatives to the treatment and prevention of malaria in P_G women, understanding of how the physiologic changes of P_G may alter the pharmacokinetics, and therefore potentially the efficacy, of artemisinin derivatives is relatively limited.
in a recent non-compartmental pharmacokinetic study, the P_K of dha was determined to be faster in P_G women than non-P_G controls, but not than in the same women three months P_G [7].

the objective of this analysis was to utilize a population pharmacokinetic approach to model the pharmacokinetics of oral as, a water soluble artemisinin derivative, and its active metabolite dha, in P_G women and controls and to identify clinically relevant covariates associated with inter-individual variability in as and dha pharmacokinetics.
for P_G S_T_U_D_Y, pharmacokinetic studies were conducted both at the time of enrollment, as well as at three months P_G.

although not statistically significant in the full covariate analysis, the effect of P_G status on dha volume of distribution was the only tested covariate relationship, apart from P_G status on clm/f, that was significant (p < 0.05) in the first forward addition step of covariate modelling.
P_G was associated with a trend towards V_E_R_B dha volume of distribution of approximately 37%.

because kidney function, as measured by P_K, is known to V_E_R_B during P_G and clonidine is predominantly eliminated by the kidneys in nonpregnant S_T_U_D_Y, we hypothesized that P_G may alter the pharmacokinetics of clonidine.
indeed, the P_G S_T_U_D_Y in our study have a significantly V_E_R_B apparent oral P_K of clonidine than previously reported in nonP_G healthy male and female S_T_U_D_Y with similar S_T_U_D_Y ranges.

although we expect that intestinal blood flow may be V_E_R_B as a result of the V_E_R_B cardiac output during P_G, this would probably result in V_E_R_B P_K and V_E_R_B plasma P_K rather than the V_E_R_B P_K seen during P_G.
even if the percentage bound for clonidine V_E_R_B to zero during P_G, it would not explain the changes seen in clonidine apparent oral P_K.
accordingly, alteration in hepatic and/or intestinal intrinsic clearances are the most likely reasons for the V_E_R_B apparent oral clearance of clonidine during P_G.

a V_E_R_B recovery of unchanged drug in the urine was observed in our P_G women compared with data reported for nonP_G S_T_U_D_Y (36% versus 59%), which is entirely consistent with the hypothesis that P_G shifts the major route of P_K for clonidine from the kidneys to organs involved in drug metabolism (davies et al., 1977; arndts, 1983).

P_G women are five to six times more likely than nonP_G women to suffer from venous thromboembolism.1 in the presence of acquired or congenital thrombophilia, the risk is even V_E_R_B for developing venous thromboembolism during P_G, especially in women with a history of prior thromboembolic events.2Ã”Ã¸Î©4 there has been an ongoing shift from the earlier use of unfractionated heparin to the current use of V_E_R_B-molecular-weight heparin (lmwh) in P_G, both for prophylaxis and for treatment of thrombotic diseases.5,6 moreover, the results from certain clinical studies have further extended the use of lmwh during P_G, because they showed that enoxaparin may prevent P_G loss in women with acquired or constitutional thrombophilia.7Ã”Ã¸Î©9 however, whether the dosing regimen defined on the basis of studies on a nonP_G population can be adopted in P_G is a matter that requires investigation.10 some studies have reported the failure of lwmh in preventing prosthetic heart valve thrombosis in P_G women.11Ã”Ã¸Î©13 the pharmacokinetics of enoxaparin may be affected by physiological changes occurring during P_G, such as a rapid V_E_R_B in renal function,14,15 which determines enoxaparin P_K,16Ã”Ã¸Î©18 and an V_E_R_B in plasma volume,14,15 which is closely linked to the enoxaparin volume of distribution.
